AB  - This paper estimates the equilibrium effect of elections on public policy in the Indian states—a valuable laboratory to study political cycles in a developing country with a history of regular elections and stable democracy. A methodological innovation employed here is to instrument for the potential endogeneity of the election cycle by distinguishing between constitutionally scheduled and early midterm elections. We find a pattern of policy manipulation that point to election-year targeting of special interest groups possibly in return for campaign support, as opposed to populist spending sprees to sway the mass of voters.
